e)\n| [[UFC 36]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2002|March|22}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 2:06\n| Las Vegas, Nevada, United States\n| \n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 4\u20134\u20131\n| [[Tito Ortiz]]\n| TKO (punches and elbows)\n| [[UFC 32]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2001|June|29}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 3:32\n| [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]], United States\n| {{small|For the [[UFC Light Heavyweight Championship]]}}\n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 4\u20133\u20131\n| [[Jeremy Horn]]\n| Submission (triangle armbar)\n| [[UFC 30]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2001|February|23}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 2:59\n| [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]], United States\n| \n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 3\u20133\u20131\n| [[Frank Shamrock]]\n| Decision\n| K-1 Grand Prix 2000 Final\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2000|December|12}}\n| align=center| 5\n| align=center| 3:00\n| Tokyo, Japan\n| \n|-\n| {{draw}}Draw\n| align=center| 3\u20132\u20131\n| [[Dave Beneteau]]\n| Draw\n| UCC 1 \u2013 The New Beginning\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2000|June|2}}\n| align=center| 2\n| align=center| 10:00\n| [[Montreal, Quebec]], Canada\n| \n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 3\u20132\n| Al Reynish\n| TKO (retirement)\n| [[1998 in Fighting Network Rings#Rings Australia: NR2|Rings Australia: NR2]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1998|September|13}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 7:52\n| Australia\n| \n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 3\u20131\n| Daniel Bond\n| TKO\n| AVT \u2013 Australia Vale Tudo\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1997|November|16}}\n| align=center| 1\n| \n| Australia\n| \n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 2\u20131\n| Kevin McConachie\n| TKO\n| AVT \u2013 Australia Vale Tudo\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1997|November|16}}\n| align=center| 1\n| \n| Australia\n| \n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 1\u20131\n| [[Chris Haseman]]\n| TKO (chin to the eye)\n| Caged Combat 1 \u2013 Australian Ultimate Fighting\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1997|March|22}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 2:47\n| Sydney, Australia\n| \n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 1\u20130\n| Matt Rocca\n| TKO (submission to strikes)\n| Caged Combat 1 \u2013 Australian Ultimate Fighting\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1997|March|22}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 0:41\n| Sydney, Australia\n| \n{{end}}\n\n==Kings Academy MMA==\nSinosic runs Kings Academy, a martial arts school located in Sydney, Australia teaching [[Brazilian Jiu Jitsu]], [[Muay Thai]], [[kickboxing]], [[mixed martial arts]], [[wrestling]] and [[hot yoga]]. Kings Academy was established in 2017. \n\nPrior to being known as Kings Academy, from 2002 till 2017 Elvis Sinosic and Anthony Perosh both held the title of \"Chief Instructor\" together at SPMA (Sinosic/Perosh Martial Arts) which was located in two different locations in Sydney. Both Instructors decided to open their Individual Gyms after they agreed that one instructor should be at one location to pay closer attention to their students.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.elvissinosic.com}}\n* {{Sherdog}}\n* {{UFC|Elvis-Sinosic}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sinosic, Elvis}}\n[[Category:Australian male mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Light heavyweight mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Ultimate Fighting Championship male fighters]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian practitioners of Brazilian jiu-jitsu]]\n[[Category:Australian male taekwondo practitioners]]\n[[Category:Australian capoeira practitioners]]\n[[Category:Australian jujutsuka]]\n[[Category:Australian Muay Thai practitioners]]\n[[Category:Australian male sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Australian submission wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Silat practitioners]]\n[[Category:Pankration practitioners]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Croatian descent]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Canberra]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP refimprove|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{short description|Australian mixed martial arts fighter}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name            = Elvis Sinosic\n| other_names     = The King of Rock n' Rumble\n| image           = Elvis king of rock n rumble.jpg\n| image_size      = 200px\n| alt             =\n| caption         =\n| birth_name      =\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|df=yes|year=1971|month=2|day=13}}\n| birth_place     = [[Canberra]], [[Australia]]\n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| death_cause     =\n| residence       = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n| nationality     =  Australian\n| height          = {{height|ft=6|in=3}}\n| weight          = {{convert|205|lb|kg st|abbr=on}}\n\n| weight_class    = [[Light heavyweight (MMA)|Light Heavyweight]]\n| reach           = {{convert|77+1/2|in|cm|abbr=on}}\n| style           = \n| stance          = Orthodox\n| fighting_out_of = Sydney, New South Wales, Australia\n| team            = Kings Academy of Martial Arts\n| rank            = 4th Degree Black belt in [[Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu]] under [[Carlos Machado (fighter)|Carlos Machado]]<br> 1st degree black belt in [[Taekwondo]]<br>Yellow rope in [[Capoeira]]<br>Orange belt in [[Judo]]<br>Brown belt in [[Silat]]<br>Full instructor in [[Eskrima]]<br>Full instructor in [[Muay Thai]]\n| years_active    = 1997-2007,  2010\n| mma_kowin       = 4\n| mma_subwin      = 4\n| mma_decwin      =\n| mma_koloss      = 7\n| mma_subloss     =\n| mma_decloss     = 4\n| mma_draw        = 2\n| mma_nc          =\n| url             =\n| sherdog         = 281\n| footnotes       =\n| updated         =\n}}\n\n'''Elvis Sinosic''' (born 13 February 1971 in [[Canberra]], Australia) is a retired Australian professional [[mixed martial artist]]. Perhaps best known for his seven-fight stint in the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC), where he ultimately accumulated a 1-6 record, he also competed in the [[Cage Rage Championships]], [[K-1]], and [[Pancrase]]. Sinosic fought for the [[UFC Light Heavyweight Championship]] at [[UFC 32]].\n\n==Biography==\nSinosic was born in Canberra, Australia to [[Croats|Croatian]] immigrant parents, and now resides in Sydney, Australia. He currently runs Sinosic Perosh Martial Arts SPMA<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spma.net.au|title=SPMA \u2013 Best Sydney club with MMA, BJJ, Kickboxing classes and training|website=Spma.net.au|accessdate=1 August 2016}}</ref> with business and training partner [[Anthony Perosh]]. Having trained in various arts for over 20 years dating back to his early twenties, Sinosic was exposed to a myriad of art forms including: [[Freestyle Wrestling]], [[Tae Kwon Do]], [[boxing]], [[Jeet kune do]], [[Filipino martial arts]], [[Silat]], [[Muay Thai]], [[Capoeira]], [[Kickboxing]], [[Judo]], [[John Will (fighter)|JB Will]] [[Shootfighting]], [[Pankration]], [[Jujutsu]] and Machado BJJ.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spma.net.au/instructors.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=8 October 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090913194658/http://www.spma.net.au/instructors.php |archivedate=13 September 2009  }}</ref>\n\nCompeting on an international level for major organizations such as the [[Abu Dhabi]] World Submission Championships, the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] and the [[K-1|K-1 Grand Prix]], Sinosic also fought in [[Pancrase]], [[RINGS]], Warriors Realm, Fighter Extreme, Universal Combat Challenge (UCC) (now called TKO Major League MMA (TKO)), [[Cage Rage]], Australian Vale Tudo Open and Caged Combat.\n\n==Mixed martial arts career==\nConsidered by some to be a pioneer of Australian mixed martial arts, Sinosic fought on the first ever Australian MMA show, Caged Combat. He competed for and won the first ever Australian MMA title, the Australian Vale Tudo Heavyweight Championship. He was also the first Australian to fight for a nominal World Title (Universal Combat Challenge 1 vs Dave Beneteau), and was the first Australian to fight in an MMA match in [[K-1]] when he lost at the [[K-1 World Grand Prix 2000]] vs Frank Shamrock. He was also the first Australian to fight in the UFC - [[UFC 30]] vs [[Jeremy Horn]] - his only winning performance with the organization, where he was the first Australian to fight for a UFC World Championship ([[UFC 32]] in a loss vs. [[Tito Ortiz]]). Sinosic was also  the first Australian to compete in the ADCC World Submission Wrestling Championships when he competed in the inaugural event in 1998, defeating unheralded grappler Clarence Thatch before being submitted by [[Renato Verissimo]]/\n\n===UFC career===\nSinosic is a UFC veteran holding a record of 1 win and 6 losses within the UFC, at the time the statistically worst record in promotional history, contributing to the 8 wins, 12 losses and 2 draws in his mixed martial arts career. He made his UFC debut defeating [[Jeremy Horn]] by [[armbar]] at [[UFC 30]], considered a huge upset at the time, and was then offered a match with [[Tito Ortiz]], who was then the [[UFC Light Heavyweight Championship|UFC Light Heavyweight Champion]] at [[UFC 32]]. Sinosic was defeated by Ortiz in the first round via [[Technical knockout]] (TKO).\n\nSubsequently, he fought several times in the UFC, with matches against [[Evan Tanner]] (TKO loss), [[Renato Sobral]] (decision loss), [[Forrest Griffin]] (KO loss), and [[Alessio Sakara]] (decision loss) at [[UFC 57]]. Following his historically unsuccessful stint with the UFC, he defeated regional fighters Shamoji Fuiji and [[Mark Epstein]] both by [[armbar]].\n\nSinosic's last fight in the UFC was a loss to [[Michael Bisping]] due to TKO (strikes) at [[UFC 70]].\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://martialarts.about.com/od/eventsandcompetitions/ig/UFC-70-Results/UFC-70---Bisping-vs-Sinosic.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=17 February 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080217024014/http://martialarts.about.com/od/eventsandcompetitions/ig/UFC-70-Results/UFC-70---Bisping-vs-Sinosic.htm |archivedate=17 February 2008  }}</ref> He was scheduled to return to the octagon in 2010 for a rematch against [[Chris Haseman]] at [[UFC 110]], the first UFC event to be held in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2010/02/15/elvis-sinosic-chris-haseman-a-terrible-fight-the-fans-will-love |title=Archived copy |accessdate=20 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080217024014/https://web.archive.org/web/20100220132550/www.mmafighting.com/2010/02/15/elvis-sinosic-chris-haseman-a-terrible-fight-the-fans-will-love |archivedate=20 February 2010 }}</ref> However, just days before the fight, Sinosic was forced to withdraw with a shoulder injury.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ufc.com/index.cfm?fa=news.detail&gid=78621 |title=The Official Website of the Ultimate Fighting Championship\u00ae (UFC) |website=Ufc.com |accessdate=1 August 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100222195720/http://www.ufc.com/index.cfm?fa=news.detail&gid=78621 |archivedate=22 February 2010  }}</ref> Following what the promotion perceived to be an elective surgical procedure that would not have prevented him from competing against Haseman, Sinosic was permanently cut by the promotion and never offered another contract.\n\n===Post UFC===\nSinosic's last fight was a KO loss to [[Paul Cahoon]] at [[List of Cage Rage events|Cage Rage 24]] on 1 December 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixedmartialarts.com/mma.cfm?go=stats.fighterDetail&pid=B399C7A989B194A4|title=Mixed Martial Arts: MMA News, Fighters, Events, Forum|website=Mixedmartialarts.com|accessdate=1 August 2016}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Other media==\nSinosic's knockout loss to [[Forrest Griffin]] appeared in the 2007 film ''[[Next (2007 film)|Next]]'' starring [[Nicolas Cage]] and [[Jessica Biel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ebioyg75ePk|title=Elvis cameo's in NEXT|website=Youtube.com|accessdate=1 August 2016}}</ref> He also appeared on UFC Fight Week in Australia as an analyst which occasionally featured a segment known as \"MMA 101\" in which Elvis shows a short visual demonstration on a particular technique.  \n\nSinosic claimed to be the first person to perform a [[Gogoplata]] in MMA competition,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aVyO3Un9lfE|title=YouTube|website=Youtube.com|accessdate=1 August 2016}}</ref> although his opponent did not submit.\n<gallery>\nFile:Gogo By the King.jpg|Sinosic's attempted [[Gogoplata]] vs. Tamura, 14 October 1997\n</gallery>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]'''\n**[[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Fight of the Night]] (One time) <small>vs. [[Michael Bisping]] </small>\n\n==Mixed martial arts record==\n{{MMArecordbox\n| draws= 2\n| nc= \n| ko-wins= 4\n| ko-losses= 7\n| sub-wins= 4\n| sub-losses=\n| dec-wins= \n| dec-losses= 4\n| dq-wins= \n| dq-losses= \n| other-wins= \n| other-losses= \n}}\n{{MMA record start}}\n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 8\u201311\u20132\n| [[Paul Cahoon]]\n| KO (punches)\n| [[2007 in Cage Rage Championships#Cage Rage 24|Cage Rage 24]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2007|December|1}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 0:21\n| [[London]], United Kingdom\n| \n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 8\u201310\u20132\n| [[Michael Bisping]]\n| TKO (punches)\n| [[UFC 70]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2007|April|21}}\n| align=center| 2\n| align=center| 1:40\n| [[Manchester]], United Kingdom\n| {{small|Fight of the Night.}}\n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 8\u20139\u20132\n| Mark Epstein\n| Submission (armbar)\n| [[2006 in Cage Rage Championships#Cage Rage 19|Cage Rage 19]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2006|December|9}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 2:37\n| [[London]], United Kingdom\n| \n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 7\u20139\u20132\n| Shamoji Fuji\n| Submission (armbar)\n| Xplosion\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2006|September|30}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 2:40\n| [[Sydney]], Australia\n| \n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 6\u20139\u20132\n| [[Alessio Sakara]]\n| Decision (unanimous)\n| [[UFC 57|UFC 57: Liddell vs. Couture 3]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2006|February|4}}\n| align=center| 3\n| align=center| 5:00\n| [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], United States\n| \n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 6\u20138\u20132\n| [[Forrest Griffin]]\n| KO (punches)\n| [[UFC 55|UFC 55: Fury]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2005|October|7}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 3:22\n| [[Uncasville, Connecticut]], United States\n| \n|-\n| {{draw}}Draw\n| align=center| 6\u20137\u20132\n| [[Daijiro Matsui]]\n| Draw\n| [[2005 in Pancrase#Pancrase: Spiral 5|Pancrase: Spiral 5]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2005|July|10}}\n| align=center| 2\n| align=center| 5:00\n| [[Yokohama]], Japan\n| \n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 6\u20137\u20131\n| [[Roberto Traven]]\n| KO (punch)\n| WR 1 \u2013 Warriors Realm 1\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2004|September|3}}\n| align=center| 2\n| \n| [[Sunshine Coast, Queensland]]\n| \n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 5\u20137\u20131\n| [[Sanae Kikuta]]\n| Decision (unanimous)\n| [[2003 in Pancrase#Pancrase - 10th Anniversary Show|Pancrase - 10th Anniversary Show]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2003|August|31}}\n| align=center| 3\n| align=center| 5:00\n| [[Tokyo]], Japan\n| \n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 5\u20136\u20131\n| August Wallen\n| Submission (armbar)\n| FE 3 \u2013 Fighter Extreme 3\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2003|May|2}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 5:36\n| [[Stockholm]], Sweden\n| \n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 4\u20136\u20131\n| [[Renato Sobral]]\n| Decision (unanimous)\n| [[UFC 38]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2002|July|13}}\n| align=center| 3\n| align=center| 5:00\n| [[London]], United Kingdom\n| \n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 4\u20135\u20131\n| [[Evan Tanner]]\n| TKO (doctor stoppage)\n| [[UFC 36]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2002|March|22}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 2:06\n| Las Vegas, Nevada, United States\n| \n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 4\u20134\u20131\n| [[Tito Ortiz]]\n| TKO (punches and elbows)\n| [[UFC 32]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2001|June|29}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 3:32\n| [[East Rutherford, New Jersey]], United States\n| {{small|For the [[UFC Light Heavyweight Championship]]}}\n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 4\u20133\u20131\n| [[Jeremy Horn]]\n| Submission (triangle armbar)\n| [[UFC 30]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2001|February|23}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 2:59\n| [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]], United States\n| \n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 3\u20133\u20131\n| [[Frank Shamrock]]\n| Decision\n| K-1 Grand Prix 2000 Final\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2000|December|12}}\n| align=center| 5\n| align=center| 3:00\n| Tokyo, Japan\n| \n|-\n| {{draw}}Draw\n| align=center| 3\u20132\u20131\n| [[Dave Beneteau]]\n| Draw\n| UCC 1 \u2013 The New Beginning\n| {{dts|format=dmy|2000|June|2}}\n| align=center| 2\n| align=center| 10:00\n| [[Montreal, Quebec]], Canada\n| \n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 3\u20132\n| Al Reynish\n| TKO (retirement)\n| [[1998 in Fighting Network Rings#Rings Australia: NR2|Rings Australia: NR2]]\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1998|September|13}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 7:52\n| Australia\n| \n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 3\u20131\n| Daniel Bond\n| TKO\n| AVT \u2013 Australia Vale Tudo\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1997|November|16}}\n| align=center| 1\n| \n| Australia\n| \n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 2\u20131\n| Kevin McConachie\n| TKO\n| AVT \u2013 Australia Vale Tudo\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1997|November|16}}\n| align=center| 1\n| \n| Australia\n| \n|-\n| {{no2}}Loss\n| align=center| 1\u20131\n| [[Chris Haseman]]\n| TKO (chin to the eye)\n| Caged Combat 1 \u2013 Australian Ultimate Fighting\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1997|March|22}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 2:47\n| Sydney, Australia\n| \n|-\n| {{yes2}}Win\n| align=center| 1\u20130\n| Matt Rocca\n| TKO (submission to strikes)\n| Caged Combat 1 \u2013 Australian Ultimate Fighting\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1997|March|22}}\n| align=center| 1\n| align=center| 0:41\n| Sydney, Australia\n| \n{{end}}\n\n==Kings Academy MMA==\nSinosic runs Kings Academy, a martial arts school located in Sydney, Australia teaching [[Brazilian Jiu Jitsu]], [[Muay Thai]], [[kickboxing]], [[mixed martial arts]], [[wrestling]] and [[hot yoga]]. Kings Academy was established in 2017. \n\nPrior to being known as Kings Academy, from 2002 till 2017 Elvis Sinosic and Anthony Perosh both held the title of \"Chief Instructor\" together at SPMA (Sinosic/Perosh Martial Arts) which was located in two different locations in Sydney. Both Instructors decided to open their Individual Gyms after they agreed that one instructor should be at one location to pay closer attention to their students.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.elvissinosic.com}}\n* {{Sherdog}}\n* {{UFC|Elvis-Sinosic}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sinosic, Elvis}}\n[[Category:Australian male mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Light heavyweight mixed martial artists]]\n[[Category:Ultimate Fighting Championship male fighters]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian practitioners of Brazilian jiu-jitsu]]\n[[Category:Australian male taekwondo practitioners]]\n[[Category:Australian capoeira practitioners]]\n[[Category:Australian jujutsuka]]\n[[Category:Australian Muay Thai practitioners]]\n[[Category:Australian male sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Australian submission wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Silat practitioners]]\n[[Category:Pankration practitioners]]\n[[Category:Australian people of Croatian descent]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Canberra]]\n", "name_user": "HistoryFightFan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elvis_Sinosic"}
{"title_page": "Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)", "text_new": "{{short description|Professional wrestling company}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name=Universal Wrestling Federation\n|image=[[File:Logo of the defunct Universal Wrestling Federation owned by Herb Abrams from 1990-1996.jpg|220px]]\n|type=[[Private company|Private]]\n|fate=Assets acquired by Al Burke\n|foundation=August 26, 1990\n|defunct=July 23, 1996\n|founder=[[Herb Abrams]]\n|area_served = Worldwide\n|location=[[Marina del Rey, California]]\n|industry=[[Professional wrestling]]\n|products=Television, Merchandise\n}}\n\n'''Universal Wrestling Federation''' ('''UWF''') was an American [[professional wrestling]] [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotion]] owned by [[Herb Abrams]] from 1990 to 1996. The company aired nationally on [[SportsChannel America]], and later on [[Prime Ticket]] and [[ESPN2]]. \n\nA Season 2 episode of ''[[Dark Side of the Ring]]'' focused on the promotion will air in May 2020.<ref>https://www.tvinsider.com/927543/dark-side-of-the-ring-season-2-premiere-chris-benoit/</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Herb Abrams]] founded the UWF in 1990 to try and challenge [[Vince McMahon]]'s [[World Wrestling Federation]] on a national level. He announced the promotion's formation at John Arezzi's ''Wrestling Fans Fantasy Weekend'' convention in August 1990. Despite having no experience in the wrestling business, Abrams was given a budget of $1 million by [[SportsChannel America]] to develop a weekly television series, which would become ''Fury Hour''.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 134.</ref> The first ''Fury Hour'' tapings were held at [[Reseda Country Club]] in the Fall of 1990 and featured established stars such as [[Paul Orndorff]], [[\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams|Steve Williams]], [[Don Muraco]], [[Bob Orton, Jr.]], [[Brian Blair]], [[Dan Spivey]], [[Billy Jack Haynes]], [[Ken Patera]], [[Colonel DeBeers]], [[David Sammartino]], [[Ivan Koloff]], and [[Mick Foley|Cactus Jack]].<ref name=mf184>Foley, Mick. Have A Nice Day: A Tale of Blood and Sweatsocks (p.184)</ref> The top homegrown talent included \"Wild Thing\" Steve Ray and \"Cutie Pie\" [[Louie Spicolli]]. [[Bruno Sammartino]] and [[Lou Albano]] were hired as commentators.\n\nThe promotion held a taping in [[New York City]] at the [[New York Penta]] in January 1991 that was plagued with legal issues. The World Wrestling Federation sent cease and desist orders after [[The Honky Tonk Man|Honky Tonk Man]] and [[Rick Rude]] appeared on-camera.<ref name=02041991WON>{{cite web|url=https://members.f4wonline.com/wrestling-observer-newsletter/feb-4-1991-observer-newsletter-pivotal-week-life-dave-meltzer-89881|title=February 4, 1991 Observer Newsletter: Pivotal week in the life of Dave Meltzer|author=Observer Staff|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|website=F4WOnline.com|date=February 4, 1991|accessdate=September 7, 2019}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Both had recently walked out of the WWF but were still under contract to the company. Honky Tonk Man would later explain that the check he received from Abrams for this taping bounced, and he filed a formal complaint with the [[New York State Athletic Commission]] to get reimbursed.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9r6kIfzFSSM</ref>\n\nAbrams hired Howard Brody, the owner of [[Ladies Major League Wrestling]], to help him expand UWF into the Florida market in mid-1991.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 149.</ref> Following several house shows and a television taping at [[Universal Studios Florida]], Brody was entrusted with finding a venue for the promotion's first [[pay per view]] event in June 1991. Brody suggested the [[Odeum Expo Center]] in Chicago. Abrams insisted on holding [[Beach Brawl]] at [[Manatee Civic Center]] in [[Palmetto, FL]].<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 156.</ref> The pay per view was a disaster in both attendance and pay per view buys. Following Beach Brawl, Abrams ran one final television taping in Florida before running out of fresh footage for ''Fury Hour''. He struck a deal with Brody to use footage from Ladies Major League Wrestling to fulfill his obligations with SportsChannel America, and the two parted ways in the Fall of 1991.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 163.</ref>\n\nAbrams would only run three more shows after his initial SportsChannel America deal expired in late 1991. This included a television taping at [[Spartanburg Memorial Auditorium]] in June 1992 that aired on [[Prime Ticket]] as ''Thunder Hour'', a television taping at [[North Dakota State Fair]] in July 1993 that was never aired, and the [[Blackjack Brawl]] show at [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in September 1994. The latter show aired live on SportsChannel America and was a disaster in both attendance and television ratings.\n\nAbrams left for New York City to take care of his ailing mother in December 1994, and wrestler Al Burke was put in charge of the company.<ref>http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewalburke.htm</ref> [[Zoogz Rift]] also worked for the company during this time, and claimed Abrams' addiction to [[cocaine]] drained the company of money needed to do further shows.<ref>http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewzoogzrift2.htm</ref> [[ESPN2]] briefly aired old episodes of ''Fury Hour'' in 1995, albeit in heavily edited form. Abrams died of a heart attack in July 1996 while still in New York.\n\nAl Burke claimed ownership of the UWF tape library as abandoned property following the death of Abrams. In recent years, Burke partnered with Todd Okerlund of Classic Wrestling to repackage and license the library through [[DirecTV]] and [[ESPN Classic (Canada)|ESPN Classic Canada]].\n\n==Major events==\n===Beach Brawl===\n{{main|UWF Beach Brawl}}\nUWF held two major events during its run. The first event, Beach Brawl, was the only pay-per-view event in the company's history and was held on June 7, 1991 at the [[Bradenton Area Convention Center|Manatee Civic Center]] in [[Palmetto, Florida]]. The event was headlined by a match between [[Steve Williams (wrestler)|Steve Williams]] and [[Bam Bam Bigelow]], which was the final round match of a sixteen-man tournament for the crowning of the first [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF SportsChannel Television Championship|UWF SportsChannel Television Champion]]. Williams defeated Bigelow to become the first SportsChannel Television Champion. The event was an overall failure with a low buyrate of 0.1 and a crowd of 500 in attendance at the arena.\n\n===Blackjack Brawl===\n{{main|UWF Blackjack Brawl}}\nAfter the failure of Beach Brawl, UWF decided to air a live television special called Blackjack Brawl on September 23, 1994 on [[SportsChannel America]], which was UWF's last major attempt to secure a major television deal and survive in the professional wrestling industry. The event was held at the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]]. Like its predecessor Beach Brawl, the event saw very low attendance of just 600 fans and received negative response from critics and audiences for weak quality, weakly performed matches, nonsense booking and weak commentary. The event featured nine championship matches, with two vacant championships being decided at the event, and seven new championships being contested at the event. The event was headlined by a [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Heavyweight Championship|UWF World Heavyweight Championship]] match between defending champion Steve Williams and [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]]. The event was received negatively by fans especially due to the main event match ending in a disqualification, and this was UWF's final show.\n\n==''Fury Hour''==\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name = UWF Fury Hour\n|image = UWF Fury Hour.JPG\n|creator = [[Herb Abrams]]\n|caption = ''UWF Fury Hour'' logo\n|picture_format = [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n|camera = [[Multiple-camera setup|Multicamera setup]]\n|runtime = 60 minutes (including commercials)\n|company = Abrams Productions\n|executive_producer = Lenny Duge\n|starring = See [[List of former Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) personnel|UWF alumni]]\n|country = United States\n|location = [[Reseda Country Club]] <small>(1990)</small><br>[[New York Penta]] <small>(1991)</small><br>[[Universal Studios Florida]] <small>(1991)</small><br>[[War Memorial Auditorium]] <small>(1991)</small><br>[[Spartanburg Memorial Auditorium]] <small>(1992)</small>\n|network = [[SportsChannel America]] <small>(1990-1991)</small><br>[[Prime Ticket]] <small>(1992)</small><br>[[ESPN2]] <small>(1995)</small>\n|first_aired = October 1, 1990\n|last_aired = July 26, 1992\n|num_episodes = 69\n|list_episodes = List of UWF Fury Hour episodes\n|opentheme = \"[[The Equalizer#Music|The Equalizer Busy Equalizing]]\" by [[Stewart Copeland]]\n|website = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0821416/\n}}\n\nIn 1990, the company signed a one-year television deal with [[SportsChannel America]]. A weekly program called '''''Fury Hour''''' debuted in October 1990, and aired on Monday nights as part of the network's ''Feet, Fists and Fury'' programming block that also included [[kickboxing]] and [[boxing]].<ref>https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/90-OCR/BC-1990-09-17-OCR-Page-0043.pdf</ref>\n\nA famous [[Shoot (professional wrestling)|shoot]] occurred during a semifinal [[UWF Beach Brawl#SportsChannel Television Championship tournament brackets|SportsChannel Television Championship Tournament]] match between Steve Ray and [[Steve Williams (wrestler)|Steve Williams]] in May 1991. Allegedly, [[Herb Abrams]] thought Ray was sleeping with his wife and paid Williams extra money to rough Ray up during the bout. Ray would claim years later that this was a [[worked shoot]] and both competitors had agreed to work stiff with each other prior to the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewzoogzrift2.htm|title=UWF - Interview - Zoogz Rift|website=herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3lkjnUCA7tA|title=Wrestling With Wregret - UWF|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gfwX767OOPY</ref>\n\nAbrams signed a deal with [[Prime Ticket]] in June 1992 for the production and broadcast of new content.<ref>Meltzer, Dave. ''Wrestling Observer Newsletter''. July 6, 1992, p. 14.</ref> New episodes taped at [[Spartanburg Memorial Auditorium]] aired as '''''Thunder Hour''''' on Sunday nights, and ''Fury Hour'' reruns began airing on Saturday mornings.\n\nIn March 1995, existing ''Fury Hour'' and ''Thunder Hour'' episodes were repackaged to a half-hour format and aired daily on [[ESPN2]]. Those same 24 repackaged episodes later re-aired on [[ESPN Classic]] in 2008 and 2009.<ref>[http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/tv_reports/index_topic/topic/10301 411mania \u00bb Wrestling \u00bb TV Reports] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922193027/http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/tv_reports/index_topic/topic/10301 |date=September 22, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/espnclassic.htm|title=UWF - ESPN Classic|website=herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com}}</ref>Steve Ray tried suing ESPN Classic in 2014 for using his likeness during these rebroadcasts, but was unsuccessful.<ref>https://www.wrestlinginc.com/news/2015/04/espn-win-in-wrestling-footage-case-upheld-on-appeal-592704/</ref>\n\n[[ESPN Classic (Canada)|ESPN Classic Canada]] reran original one-hour format episodes of ''Fury Hour'' in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2004/01/21/320155.html|title=ESPN Classics Canada won't go Raw|publisher=SLAM Wrestling|date=January 21, 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Commentators===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Commentators\n!Tenure\n|-\n|[[Herb Abrams]] and [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n|September 24, 1990 - November 11, 1990\n|-\n|[[Craig Minervini|Craig DeGeorge]] and [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n|December 6, 1990 - July 20, 1991\n|-\n|Craig DeGeorge and [[Lou Albano]] \n|April 7, 1991\n|-\n|Craig DeGeorge and [[John Tolos]] \n|June 19, 1992\n|-\n|Carlo Gianelli and John Tolos\n|July 24, 1993 - September 23, 1994\n|-\n|}\n\n===Commissioners===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Commissioner\n! Date started\n! Date finished\n|-\n| Arnold Ross\n| September 24, 1990\n| October 11, 1990\n|-\n| Carlo Gianelli\n| July 24, 1993\n| July 24, 1993\n|-\n| [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n| September 23, 1994\n| September 23, 1994\n|-\n|}\n\n===Recurring segments===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Segment\n! Segment Type\n! Host(s)\n! Years Active\n|-\n|Ask The Wrestlers\n|Interview\n|[[Herb Abrams]]\n|1990 - 1991\n|-\n|Captain Lou's Corner\n|Interview\n|[[Lou Albano]]\n|1990 - 1991\n|-\n|To the Point\n|Interview\n|[[Lou Albano]] and [[Herb Abrams]]\n|1991\n|-\n|Colonel Red's Corner\n|Interview\n|Colonel Red\n|1992\n|-\n|}\n\n==Championships==\n\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Americas Championship|UWF Americas Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship|UWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship]] (1993)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Israeli Championship|UWF Israeli Championship]] (1991)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Junior Heavyweight Championship|UWF Junior Heavyweight Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF MGM Grand Championship|UWF MGM Grand Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Midget World Championship|UWF Midget World Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF North American Championship|UWF North American Championship]] (1991)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Southern States Championship|UWF Southern States Championship]] (1992, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF SportsChannel Television Championship|UWF SportsChannel Television Championship]] (1991-1992, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Women's World Championship|UWF Women's World Championship]] (1991, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Heavyweight Championship|UWF World Heavyweight Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Tag Team Championship|UWF World Tag Team Championship]] (1994)\n\n==Home video==\nIn 1992, the UWF issued six [[VHS]] releases in the United States through Best Film & Video Corporation: ''Beach Brawl'', ''Tag Team Tandems'', ''The Best of Paul Orndorff'', ''The Lumberjack Match'', ''The Steel Cage Match'', and ''Wrestling's Greatest Champions''. In 1993, the UWF released six volumes of [[PAL]] videos in Germany through Summit International Pictures under the \"Wrestling Super Champs\" banner. They were all compilations of Fury Hour matches. The same six \"Wrestling Super Champs\" volumes were re-released in Germany through J\u00fcnger Verlag under the \"Super Wrestling\" banner.\n\nRecent years have seen the emergence of UWF [[DVD]]s in Australia through Payless Entertainment. Each of the seven [[DVD region code#4|Region 4]] DVDs contains one episode of ''Fury Hour''. The DVDs include ''Body Slammin'', ''Grand Slam'', ''Grudge Matches'', ''It's War'', ''Tag Team Madness'', ''The Main Event'', and ''Wrestling Wars''. In Germany, a [[DVD region code|Region 0]] DVD titled \"Wrestling Super 4 Champs\" was released containing two episodes of ''Fury Hour''. Also in Germany, the \"Wrestling Super Champs\" VHS compilations were re-released on DVD in six volumes as \"American History of Wrestling - UWF\".\n\n==Awards==\n*'''Wrestling Observer Newsletter'''\n**1990 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Announcer|Worst Television Announcer]] (Herb Abrams)\n**1991 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Promotion of the Year|Worst Promotion of the Year]] (UWF)\n**1991 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Show|Worst Television Show]] (Fury Hour)\n**1994 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Major Wrestling Show|Worst Major Wrestling Show]] (Blackjack Brawl)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of former Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) personnel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/index.htm Herb Abrams' UWF Tribute Site]\n*[http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/indy/uwf/uwfindex.html Herb Abrams' UWF] on ProWrestlingHistory.com\n*[https://archive.org/details/HerbAbramsUWF Herb Abrams' UWF] on [[Archive.org]]\n\n{{Professional wrestling in the United States}}\n{{SportsChannel America}}\n{{Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)}}\n\n[[Category:1990 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:1996 disestablishments in California]]\n[[Category:1990s American television series]]\n[[Category:1990 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1990]]\n[[Category:Companies disestablished in 1996]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:ESPN original programming]]\n[[Category:Independent professional wrestling promotions based in California]]\n[[Category:Marina del Rey, California]]\n[[Category:Prime Sports Network]]\n[[Category:SportsChannel]]\n[[Category:Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)]]\n\n[[de:Universal Wrestling Federation#UWF (Herb Abrams)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Professional wrestling company}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name=Universal Wrestling Federation\n|image=[[File:Logo of the defunct Universal Wrestling Federation owned by Herb Abrams from 1990-1996.jpg|220px]]\n|type=[[Private company|Private]]\n|fate=Assets acquired by Al Burke\n|foundation=August 26, 1990\n|defunct=July 23, 1996\n|founder=[[Herb Abrams]]\n|area_served = Worldwide\n|location=[[Marina del Rey, California]]\n|industry=[[Professional wrestling]]\n|products=Television, Merchandise\n}}\n\n'''Universal Wrestling Federation''' ('''UWF''') was an American [[professional wrestling]] [[Professional wrestling promotion|promotion]] owned by [[Herb Abrams]] from 1990 to 1996. The company aired nationally on [[SportsChannel America]], and later on [[Prime Ticket]] and [[ESPN2]]. \n\nA Season 2 episode of ''[[Dark Side of the Ring]]'' focused on the promotion will air in May 2020.<ref>https://www.tvinsider.com/927543/dark-side-of-the-ring-season-2-premiere-chris-benoit/</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Herb Abrams]] founded the UWF in 1990 to try and challenge [[Vince McMahon]]'s [[World Wrestling Federation]] on a national level. He announced the promotion's formation at John Arezzi's ''Wrestling Fans Fantasy Weekend'' convention in August 1990. Despite having no experience in the wrestling business, Abrams was given a budget of $1 million by [[SportsChannel America]] to develop a weekly television series, which would become ''Fury Hour''.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 134.</ref> The first ''Fury Hour'' tapings were held at [[Reseda Country Club]] in the Fall of 1990 and featured established stars such as [[Paul Orndorff]], [[\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams|Steve Williams]], [[Don Muraco]], [[Bob Orton, Jr.]], [[Brian Blair]], [[Dan Spivey]], [[Billy Jack Haynes]], [[Ken Patera]], [[Colonel DeBeers]], [[David Sammartino]], [[Ivan Koloff]], and [[Mick Foley|Cactus Jack]].<ref name=mf184>Foley, Mick. Have A Nice Day: A Tale of Blood and Sweatsocks (p.184)</ref> The top homegrown talent included \"Wild Thing\" Steve Ray and \"Cutie Pie\" [[Louie Spicolli]]. [[Bruno Sammartino]] and [[Lou Albano]] were hired as commentators.\n\nThe promotion held a taping in [[New York City]] at the [[New York Penta]] in January 1991 that was plagued with legal issues. The World Wrestling Federation sent cease and desist orders after [[The Honky Tonk Man|Honky Tonk Man]] and [[Rick Rude]] appeared on-camera.<ref name=02041991WON>{{cite web|url=https://members.f4wonline.com/wrestling-observer-newsletter/feb-4-1991-observer-newsletter-pivotal-week-life-dave-meltzer-89881|title=February 4, 1991 Observer Newsletter: Pivotal week in the life of Dave Meltzer|author=Observer Staff|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|website=F4WOnline.com|date=February 4, 1991|accessdate=September 7, 2019}} {{subscription required}}</ref> Both had recently walked out of the WWF but were still under contract to the company. Honky Tonk Man would later explain that the check he received from Abrams for this taping bounced, and he filed a formal complaint with the [[New York State Athletic Commission]] to get reimbursed.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9r6kIfzFSSM</ref>\n\nAbrams hired Howard Brody, the owner of [[Ladies Major League Wrestling]], to help him expand UWF into the Florida market in mid-1991.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 149.</ref> Following several house shows and a television taping at [[Universal Studios Florida]], Brody was entrusted with finding a venue for the promotion's first [[pay per view]] event in June 1991. Brody suggested the [[Odeum Expo Center]] in Chicago. Abrams insisted on holding [[Beach Brawl]] at [[Manatee Civic Center]] in [[Palmetto, FL]].<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 156.</ref> The pay per view was a disaster in both attendance and pay per view buys. Following Beach Brawl, Abrams ran one final television taping in Florida before running out of fresh footage for ''Fury Hour''. He struck a deal with Brody to use footage from Ladies Major League Wrestling to fulfill his obligations with SportsChannel America, and the two parted ways in the Fall of 1991.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas: Surviving the Politics of Professional Wrestling''. ECW Press, 2009, p. 163.</ref>\n\nAbrams would only run three more shows after his initial SportsChannel America deal expired in late 1991. This included a television taping at [[Spartanburg Memorial Auditorium]] in June 1992 that aired on [[Prime Ticket]] as ''Thunder Hour'', a television taping at [[North Dakota State Fair]] in July 1993 that was never aired, and the [[Blackjack Brawl]] show at [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in September 1994. The latter show aired live on SportsChannel America and was a disaster in both attendance and television ratings.\n\nAbrams left for New York City to take care of his ailing mother in December 1994, and wrestler Al Burke was put in charge of the company.<ref>http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewalburke.htm</ref> [[Zoogz Rift]] also worked for the company during this time, and claimed Abrams' addiction to [[cocaine]] drained the company of money needed to do further shows.<ref>http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewzoogzrift2.htm</ref> [[ESPN2]] briefly aired old episodes of ''Fury Hour'' in 1995, albeit in heavily edited form. Abrams died of a heart attack in July 1996 while still in New York.\n\nAl Burke claimed ownership of the UWF tape library as abandoned property following the death of Abrams. In recent years, Burke partnered with Todd Okerlund of Classic Wrestling to repackage and license the library through [[DirecTV]] and [[ESPN Classic (Canada)|ESPN Classic Canada]].\n\n==Major events==\n===Beach Brawl===\n{{main|UWF Beach Brawl}}\nUWF held two major events during its run. The first event, Beach Brawl, was the only pay-per-view event in the company's history and was held on June 7, 1991 at the [[Bradenton Area Convention Center|Manatee Civic Center]] in [[Palmetto, Florida]]. The event was headlined by a match between [[Steve Williams (wrestler)|Steve Williams]] and [[Bam Bam Bigelow]], which was the final round match of a sixteen-man tournament for the crowning of the first [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF SportsChannel Television Championship|UWF SportsChannel Television Champion]]. Williams defeated Bigelow to become the first SportsChannel Television Champion. The event was an overall failure with a low buyrate of 0.1 and a crowd of 500 in attendance at the arena.\n\n===Blackjack Brawl===\n{{main|UWF Blackjack Brawl}}\nAfter the failure of Beach Brawl, UWF decided to air a live television special called Blackjack Brawl on September 23, 1994 on [[SportsChannel America]], which was UWF's last major attempt to secure a major television deal and survive in the professional wrestling industry. The event was held at the [[MGM Grand Garden Arena]] in [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]]. Like its predecessor Beach Brawl, the event saw very low attendance of just 600 fans and received negative response from critics and audiences for weak quality, weakly performed matches, nonsense booking and weak commentary. The event featured nine championship matches, with two vacant championships being decided at the event, and seven new championships being contested at the event. The event was headlined by a [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Heavyweight Championship|UWF World Heavyweight Championship]] match between defending champion Steve Williams and [[Sid Eudy|Sid Vicious]]. The event was received negatively by fans especially due to the main event match ending in a disqualification, and this was UWF's final show.\n\n==''Fury Hour''==\n{{Infobox television\n|show_name = UWF Fury Hour\n|image = UWF Fury Hour.JPG\n|creator = [[Herb Abrams]]\n|caption = ''UWF Fury Hour'' logo\n|picture_format = [[480i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n|camera = [[Multiple-camera setup|Multicamera setup]]\n|runtime = 60 minutes (including commercials)\n|company = Abrams Productions\n|executive_producer = Lenny Duge\n|starring = See [[List of former Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) personnel|UWF alumni]]\n|country = United States\n|location = [[Reseda Country Club]] <small>(1990)</small><br>[[New York Penta]] <small>(1991)</small><br>[[Universal Studios Florida]] <small>(1991)</small><br>[[War Memorial Auditorium]] <small>(1991)</small><br>[[Spartanburg Memorial Auditorium]] <small>(1992)</small>\n|network = [[SportsChannel America]] <small>(1990-1991)</small><br>[[Prime Ticket]] <small>(1992)</small><br>[[ESPN2]] <small>(1995)</small>\n|first_aired = October 1, 1990\n|last_aired = July 26, 1992\n|num_episodes = 69\n|list_episodes = List of UWF Fury Hour episodes\n|opentheme = \"[[The Equalizer#Music|The Equalizer Busy Equalizing]]\" by [[Stewart Copeland]]\n|website = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0821416/\n}}\n\nIn 1990, the company signed a one-year television deal with [[SportsChannel America]]. A weekly program called '''''Fury Hour''''' debuted in October 1990, and aired on Monday nights as part of the network's ''Feet, Fists and Fury'' programming block that also included [[kickboxing]] and [[boxing]].<ref>https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/90-OCR/BC-1990-09-17-OCR-Page-0043.pdf</ref>\n\nA famous [[Shoot (professional wrestling)|shoot]] occurred during a semifinal [[UWF Beach Brawl#SportsChannel Television Championship tournament brackets|SportsChannel Television Championship Tournament]] match between Steve Ray and [[Steve Williams (wrestler)|Steve Williams]] in May 1991. Allegedly, [[Herb Abrams]] thought Ray was sleeping with his wife and paid Williams extra money to rough Ray up during the bout. Ray would claim years later that this was a [[worked shoot]] and both competitors had agreed to work stiff with each other prior to the match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/interviewzoogzrift2.htm|title=UWF - Interview - Zoogz Rift|website=herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3lkjnUCA7tA|title=Wrestling With Wregret - UWF|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gfwX767OOPY</ref>\n\nAbrams signed a deal with [[Prime Ticket]] in June 1992 for the production and broadcast of new content.<ref>Meltzer, Dave. ''Wrestling Observer Newsletter''. July 6, 1992, p. 14.</ref> New episodes taped at [[Spartanburg Memorial Auditorium]] aired as '''''Thunder Hour''''' on Sunday nights, and ''Fury Hour'' reruns began airing on Saturday mornings.\n\nIn March 1995, existing ''Fury Hour'' episodes were repackaged to a half-hour format and aired daily on [[ESPN2]]. Those same 24 repackaged episodes later re-aired on [[ESPN Classic]] in 2008 and 2009.<ref>[http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/tv_reports/index_topic/topic/10301 411mania \u00bb Wrestling \u00bb TV Reports] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922193027/http://www.411mania.com/wrestling/tv_reports/index_topic/topic/10301 |date=September 22, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/espnclassic.htm|title=UWF - ESPN Classic|website=herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com}}</ref>Steve Ray tried suing ESPN Classic in 2014 for using his likeness during these rebroadcasts, but was unsuccessful.<ref>https://www.wrestlinginc.com/news/2015/04/espn-win-in-wrestling-footage-case-upheld-on-appeal-592704/</ref>\n\n[[ESPN Classic (Canada)|ESPN Classic Canada]] reran original one-hour format episodes of ''Fury Hour'' in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2004/01/21/320155.html|title=ESPN Classics Canada won't go Raw|publisher=SLAM Wrestling|date=January 21, 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Commentators===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Commentators\n!Tenure\n|-\n|[[Herb Abrams]] and [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n|September 24, 1990 - November 11, 1990\n|-\n|[[Craig Minervini|Craig DeGeorge]] and [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n|December 6, 1990 - July 20, 1991\n|-\n|Craig DeGeorge and [[Lou Albano]] \n|April 7, 1991\n|-\n|Craig DeGeorge and [[John Tolos]] \n|June 19, 1992\n|-\n|Carlo Gianelli and John Tolos\n|July 24, 1993 - September 23, 1994\n|-\n|}\n\n===Commissioners===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Commissioner\n! Date started\n! Date finished\n|-\n| Arnold Ross\n| September 24, 1990\n| October 11, 1990\n|-\n| Carlo Gianelli\n| July 24, 1993\n| July 24, 1993\n|-\n| [[Bruno Sammartino]]\n| September 23, 1994\n| September 23, 1994\n|-\n|}\n\n===Recurring segments===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Segment\n! Segment Type\n! Host(s)\n! Years Active\n|-\n|Ask The Wrestlers\n|Interview\n|[[Herb Abrams]]\n|1990 - 1991\n|-\n|Captain Lou's Corner\n|Interview\n|[[Lou Albano]]\n|1990 - 1991\n|-\n|To the Point\n|Interview\n|[[Lou Albano]] and [[Herb Abrams]]\n|1991\n|-\n|Colonel Red's Corner\n|Interview\n|Colonel Red\n|1992\n|-\n|}\n\n==Championships==\n\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Americas Championship|UWF Americas Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship|UWF Intercontinental Heavyweight Championship]] (1993)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Israeli Championship|UWF Israeli Championship]] (1991)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Junior Heavyweight Championship|UWF Junior Heavyweight Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF MGM Grand Championship|UWF MGM Grand Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Midget World Championship|UWF Midget World Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF North American Championship|UWF North American Championship]] (1991)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Southern States Championship|UWF Southern States Championship]] (1992, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF SportsChannel Television Championship|UWF SportsChannel Television Championship]] (1991-1992, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF Women's World Championship|UWF Women's World Championship]] (1991, 1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Heavyweight Championship|UWF World Heavyweight Championship]] (1994)\n*[[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) championships#UWF World Tag Team Championship|UWF World Tag Team Championship]] (1994)\n\n==Home video==\nIn 1992, the UWF issued six [[VHS]] releases in the United States through Best Film & Video Corporation: ''Beach Brawl'', ''Tag Team Tandems'', ''The Best of Paul Orndorff'', ''The Lumberjack Match'', ''The Steel Cage Match'', and ''Wrestling's Greatest Champions''. In 1993, the UWF released six volumes of [[PAL]] videos in Germany through Summit International Pictures under the \"Wrestling Super Champs\" banner. They were all compilations of Fury Hour matches. The same six \"Wrestling Super Champs\" volumes were re-released in Germany through J\u00fcnger Verlag under the \"Super Wrestling\" banner.\n\nRecent years have seen the emergence of UWF [[DVD]]s in Australia through Payless Entertainment. Each of the seven [[DVD region code#4|Region 4]] DVDs contains one episode of ''Fury Hour''. The DVDs include ''Body Slammin'', ''Grand Slam'', ''Grudge Matches'', ''It's War'', ''Tag Team Madness'', ''The Main Event'', and ''Wrestling Wars''. In Germany, a [[DVD region code|Region 0]] DVD titled \"Wrestling Super 4 Champs\" was released containing two episodes of ''Fury Hour''. Also in Germany, the \"Wrestling Super Champs\" VHS compilations were re-released on DVD in six volumes as \"American History of Wrestling - UWF\".\n\n==Awards==\n*'''Wrestling Observer Newsletter'''\n**1990 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Announcer|Worst Television Announcer]] (Herb Abrams)\n**1991 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Promotion of the Year|Worst Promotion of the Year]] (UWF)\n**1991 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Show|Worst Television Show]] (Fury Hour)\n**1994 - [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Major Wrestling Show|Worst Major Wrestling Show]] (Blackjack Brawl)\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of former Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams) personnel]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://herbabramsuwf.googlepages.com/index.htm Herb Abrams' UWF Tribute Site]\n*[http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/indy/uwf/uwfindex.html Herb Abrams' UWF] on ProWrestlingHistory.com\n*[https://archive.org/details/HerbAbramsUWF Herb Abrams' UWF] on [[Archive.org]]\n\n{{Professional wrestling in the United States}}\n{{SportsChannel America}}\n{{Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)}}\n\n[[Category:1990 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:1996 disestablishments in California]]\n[[Category:1990s American television series]]\n[[Category:1990 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 1990]]\n[[Category:Companies disestablished in 1996]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:ESPN original programming]]\n[[Category:Independent professional wrestling promotions based in California]]\n[[Category:Marina del Rey, California]]\n[[Category:Prime Sports Network]]\n[[Category:SportsChannel]]\n[[Category:Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)]]\n\n[[de:Universal Wrestling Federation#UWF (Herb Abrams)]]\n", "name_user": "TheNewMinistry",